The Chrysanthemum fabric collection by Alison Glass for Andover Fabrics is inspired by the Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum in Boston. The museum building itself is a surprising, eclectic mix of stone and iron work throughout the rooms that surround the interior atrium. The outside of the building is quite plain, which makes the inside, with its layer upon layer of details, so intriguing. In this design, 'Iron', Alison captures one of the many pieces of iron work that add texture to the museum. ⁠
⁠
@gardnermuseum #alisonglass #agchrysanthemum #chrysanthemumfabric #andoverfabrics #IsabellaStewartGardnerMuseum⁠

Each room in the Gardner Museum is known by a different name such as The Raphael Room, The Tapestry Room, The Short Gallery, and The Blue Room. In the corner of the Yellow Room, a particular small painting caught Alison’s eye. From the doorway, it looks like a canvas painted entirely grey in a thick, ornate frame. Unlike the general busyness of so many of the other paintings and items, 'Nocturne' by James Whistler stands out because of its subtleness. Up close, tiny shadowy bits appear - a small boat on the water at night, a lighthouse far off in the distance, a few specks of orange and yellow light reflecting in the water. This design, 'Canvas', intends to capture the feel of the painting - subtle shifts in color and specks of light. 'Canvas' is part of the Chrysanthemum fabric collection by Alison Glass for Andover Fabrics, shipping in November 2023.⁠
